WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.942 --> 00:00:06.400
GARY A. HAUGEN:
Well, I didn't plan

00:00:06.400 --> 00:00:08.430
to come to Google to get
razzed about my hair,

00:00:08.430 --> 00:00:10.790
but I guess you just
don't know what to expect.

00:00:10.790 --> 00:00:13.300
So thanks for keeping
me on my toes, Justin.

00:00:13.300 --> 00:00:15.390
Thank you all for
joining me today.

00:00:15.390 --> 00:00:17.880
It's a great privilege
to get to be here.

00:00:17.880 --> 00:00:20.180
I would like to share a
little bit about the problems

00:00:20.180 --> 00:00:21.870
of violence in the
developing world,

00:00:21.870 --> 00:00:24.810
but I like to start with
a story from Oregon,

00:00:24.810 --> 00:00:25.840
the State of Oregon.

00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:27.340
And maybe some of
you are joining us

00:00:27.340 --> 00:00:31.169
from Northern
California might relate.

00:00:31.169 --> 00:00:33.210
So there's this young
woman just a few months ago

00:00:33.210 --> 00:00:35.760
who's home alone in her house.

00:00:35.760 --> 00:00:39.590
She lives in a rural area,
and just a few months before,

00:00:39.590 --> 00:00:42.660
actually, she had been
horrifically assaulted

00:00:42.660 --> 00:00:44.530
by this guy.

00:00:44.530 --> 00:00:48.160
And this guy is now at
her house, actually.

00:00:48.160 --> 00:00:49.560
It's a weekend night.

00:00:49.560 --> 00:00:51.540
She's alone, it's
dark, and this guy's

00:00:51.540 --> 00:00:54.272
actually tearing his
way into her house.

00:00:54.272 --> 00:00:55.730
And she does what
anyone else would

00:00:55.730 --> 00:00:59.300
do, she picks up to the
phone to call 911, right?

00:00:59.300 --> 00:01:01.090
And then what
proceeds to happen is

00:01:01.090 --> 00:01:07.550
the 911 operator engages this
very, very tense conversation

00:01:07.550 --> 00:01:10.350
where she explains to this
young woman that I'm sorry,

00:01:10.350 --> 00:01:13.670
but because of budget
cuts in your area,

00:01:13.670 --> 00:01:17.390
you don't have law
enforcement in your area.

00:01:17.390 --> 00:01:21.650
That there's no one that
we can send for you.

00:01:21.650 --> 00:01:24.130
Law enforcement was
available on the weekdays,

00:01:24.130 --> 00:01:26.060
but this was the weekend.

00:01:26.060 --> 00:01:28.270
And there's this
incredibly painful

00:01:28.270 --> 00:01:32.640
10 minutes of conversation
where this 911 operator realized

00:01:32.640 --> 00:01:36.100
there's just nothing that
she can do for this woman.

00:01:36.100 --> 00:01:39.440
And horrifically,
of course, the man

00:01:39.440 --> 00:01:42.440
did make his way into the house,
horrifically assaults her,

00:01:42.440 --> 00:01:43.970
and rapes her.

00:01:43.970 --> 00:01:47.120
And this story did sort of
make the news around the world,

00:01:47.120 --> 00:01:48.925
and the reason I
share it, though,

00:01:48.925 --> 00:01:53.340
is because this is an
example of what billions

00:01:53.340 --> 00:01:58.400
of poor people in the world
live in as their daily reality.

00:01:58.400 --> 00:01:59.360
Why is that?

00:01:59.360 --> 00:02:02.930
Because they don't have law
enforcement in their area.

00:02:02.930 --> 00:02:06.790
A recent UN study found that
about four billion people

00:02:06.790 --> 00:02:11.160
in the world live outside
the protection of law.

00:02:11.160 --> 00:02:13.440
And one of things we're
trying to do in this book,

00:02:13.440 --> 00:02:16.630
"The Locust Effect" is first of
all, get the news of this out.

00:02:16.630 --> 00:02:18.530
And then have us pause
together to think

00:02:18.530 --> 00:02:19.650
about that for a moment.

00:02:19.650 --> 00:02:22.360
What if billions, especially
of the poorest people

00:02:22.360 --> 00:02:26.640
in the world, don't have access
to basic law enforcement?

00:02:26.640 --> 00:02:27.886
What does that look like?

00:02:27.886 --> 00:02:29.260
Well, we know a
bit what it feels

00:02:29.260 --> 00:02:30.968
like because of this
story of this woman.

00:02:30.968 --> 00:02:33.310
But it looks like something
different in Bolivia,

00:02:33.310 --> 00:02:37.320
for instance, where according
to statistics, if you sexually

00:02:37.320 --> 00:02:40.500
assault a child in
Bolivia, you actually

00:02:40.500 --> 00:02:43.150
are at greater risk of
slipping in the shower

00:02:43.150 --> 00:02:45.410
and dying than you are of
actually being convicted

00:02:45.410 --> 00:02:46.830
for that crime.

00:02:46.830 --> 00:02:49.860
And as a result, there just
an epidemic of sexual violence

00:02:49.860 --> 00:02:52.030
against women and
girls in Bolivia.

00:02:52.030 --> 00:02:56.210
In India, amazingly,
if you enslave someone

00:02:56.210 --> 00:02:59.240
you have a greater chance
of being struck by lightning

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:02.870
than ever being actually
convicted for that crime.

00:03:02.870 --> 00:03:05.920
So this is what it looks like
in the developing world when

00:03:05.920 --> 00:03:09.616
you have this complete
collapse of law enforcement.

00:03:09.616 --> 00:03:11.490
And then what "The Locust
Effect" tries to do

00:03:11.490 --> 00:03:13.910
is then tell the
story of the violence

00:03:13.910 --> 00:03:17.310
that this collapse has unleashed
for the poorest in the world.

00:03:17.310 --> 00:03:21.000
And we go to four categories
of violence against the poor.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:23.190
The first one is what
we call gender violence.

00:03:23.190 --> 00:03:25.500
It's just sexual violence
and domestic abuse

00:03:25.500 --> 00:03:27.130
against women and girls.

00:03:27.130 --> 00:03:29.830
Which according to the
World Health Organization,

00:03:29.830 --> 00:03:32.780
it accounts for more death
and disability in the world

00:03:32.780 --> 00:03:37.130
than malaria, cancer,
car accidents, and war

00:03:37.130 --> 00:03:39.080
all combined.

00:03:39.080 --> 00:03:42.160
The greatest threat for
the average poor person

00:03:42.160 --> 00:03:44.970
in the developing world,
especially a woman or a girl

00:03:44.970 --> 00:03:47.990
is violence close at
home, sexual violence,

00:03:47.990 --> 00:03:50.300
or domestic abuse.

00:03:50.300 --> 00:03:52.660
I got to know a good
deal about this working

00:03:52.660 --> 00:03:55.060
with International
Justice Mission which,

00:03:55.060 --> 00:03:58.120
by the way, so grateful
for Google's partnership

00:03:58.120 --> 00:04:02.510
in this work trying to protect
the poorest from violence.

00:04:02.510 --> 00:04:06.470
And what we do is we have teams
in the developing world who

00:04:06.470 --> 00:04:09.480
are local indigenous
nationals, and they

00:04:09.480 --> 00:04:11.490
are lawyers, and
criminal investigators,

00:04:11.490 --> 00:04:14.620
and social workers and they take
on these cases of violent abuse

00:04:14.620 --> 00:04:17.329
and oppression on
behalf of the victims

00:04:17.329 --> 00:04:18.940
and seek justice for them.

00:04:18.940 --> 00:04:21.200
Make sure the perpetrators
are brought to justice,

00:04:21.200 --> 00:04:23.310
and make sure that we
provide long-term care

00:04:23.310 --> 00:04:25.620
for the survivors of this abuse.

00:04:25.620 --> 00:04:28.030
And so now we've been doing
this for almost 20 years,

00:04:28.030 --> 00:04:31.772
we've had 10s of thousands of
cases of this violent abuse.

00:04:31.772 --> 00:04:33.480
And it's getting to
know those cases that

00:04:33.480 --> 00:04:35.030
allows us to see the reality.

00:04:35.030 --> 00:04:40.030
And it came on for me meeting
this woman, Lucilla in Peru.

00:04:40.030 --> 00:04:44.060
Lucilla's a common
Andean mom who's

00:04:44.060 --> 00:04:45.840
trying to provide for
her little family.

00:04:45.840 --> 00:04:47.560
And as I got to know
her, I came to know

00:04:47.560 --> 00:04:49.740
the story of living
in her little town,

00:04:49.740 --> 00:04:52.120
she experienced the
horrific rape and murder

00:04:52.120 --> 00:04:53.960
of her eight-year-old
girl who was just

00:04:53.960 --> 00:04:55.130
dumped out on the street.

00:04:55.130 --> 00:04:57.706
They didn't even have
the-- I don't know.

00:04:57.706 --> 00:04:59.734
They didn't even
bother with the shame

00:04:59.734 --> 00:05:01.650
of like throwing her in
the river or anything.

00:05:01.650 --> 00:05:03.650
They just left her
out on the street.

00:05:03.650 --> 00:05:07.170
And to follow Lucilla
on the journey

00:05:07.170 --> 00:05:09.700
to see what it means
to try to get justice

00:05:09.700 --> 00:05:13.890
for such a crime when you have
no functioning law enforcement.

00:05:13.890 --> 00:05:16.180
One of things I found out
about Lucilla's little town

00:05:16.180 --> 00:05:18.310
in the Andean mountains
is that it actually

00:05:18.310 --> 00:05:22.160
had a higher rate of sexual
assault against women and girls

00:05:22.160 --> 00:05:25.920
than what was coming out of the
worst war zones of the Congo.

00:05:25.920 --> 00:05:27.500
And this was also
the idea that there

00:05:27.500 --> 00:05:29.770
can be levels of
violence taking place

00:05:29.770 --> 00:05:33.630
that maybe in the headlines
we hear about it when it's

00:05:33.630 --> 00:05:35.930
in a war, or a
conflict, or a genocide,

00:05:35.930 --> 00:05:39.820
but we're talking in this
book about everyday violence.

00:05:39.820 --> 00:05:42.830
The second category of everyday
violence that afflicts the poor

00:05:42.830 --> 00:05:45.280
is straight up slavery.

00:05:45.280 --> 00:05:48.940
The global slavery index
just came out in October,

00:05:48.940 --> 00:05:52.440
and it affirmed that there's
about 30 million people

00:05:52.440 --> 00:05:54.800
in the world who are
literally held in slavery.

00:05:54.800 --> 00:05:57.320
That's more people in slavery
than at any other time

00:05:57.320 --> 00:05:58.530
in human history.

00:05:58.530 --> 00:06:01.050
About 11 million people
were extracted from Africa

00:06:01.050 --> 00:06:04.210
during 400 years of the
transatlantic slave trade.

00:06:04.210 --> 00:06:08.540
But today, there's about
30 million held in slavery.

00:06:08.540 --> 00:06:12.580
In the book, you get the
sort of up close view of this

00:06:12.580 --> 00:06:16.410
from getting to know Mariama
and the story of her family

00:06:16.410 --> 00:06:18.090
and a number of
other villagers who

00:06:18.090 --> 00:06:20.630
were held as slaves
in a brick factory.

00:06:20.630 --> 00:06:24.210
And this is not in some
completely remote lawless

00:06:24.210 --> 00:06:25.400
part of India either.

00:06:25.400 --> 00:06:30.090
This is really just on the
beltway outside Bangalore,

00:06:30.090 --> 00:06:32.040
which is as you know
the high-tech capital

00:06:32.040 --> 00:06:33.670
in many ways of India.

00:06:33.670 --> 00:06:36.190
But it would just take
us a matter of minutes

00:06:36.190 --> 00:06:38.820
before we could be able to
drive with investigators to be

00:06:38.820 --> 00:06:41.910
able to find places
of literal slavery.

00:06:41.910 --> 00:06:46.770
So that's the second category
of violence is slavery.

00:06:46.770 --> 00:06:51.980
Third is the reality of police
abuse in the lives of the poor.

00:06:51.980 --> 00:06:54.070
The World Bank did
this global study

00:06:54.070 --> 00:06:57.519
which revealed that, it
said, police and courts

00:06:57.519 --> 00:06:59.060
in the developing
world actually make

00:06:59.060 --> 00:07:03.820
poor people less
secure and poorer.

00:07:03.820 --> 00:07:06.370
What you find is that poor
people in the developing world

00:07:06.370 --> 00:07:08.890
don't run to the police for
protection and to be safe.

00:07:08.890 --> 00:07:12.590
They run from the police
to be protected and safe.

00:07:12.590 --> 00:07:15.710
Statistics will also
show that the police are

00:07:15.710 --> 00:07:18.550
likely to actually steal more
from a common poor person

00:07:18.550 --> 00:07:20.890
than anybody else in
their community just

00:07:20.890 --> 00:07:23.980
from the daily grind of
extortion and bribery.

00:07:23.980 --> 00:07:26.150
So that's the fourth
category of violence.

00:07:26.150 --> 00:07:26.900
I mean, the third.

00:07:26.900 --> 00:07:29.870
The fourth is
violent land seizure,

00:07:29.870 --> 00:07:32.089
the way that millions of
poor people every year

00:07:32.089 --> 00:07:34.380
are threatened with having
their land stolen from them.

00:07:34.380 --> 00:07:38.860
In fact, about 5 million a
year find themselves forcibly

00:07:38.860 --> 00:07:40.780
thrown off their land.

00:07:40.780 --> 00:07:43.430
One of the largest categories
of victims of land theft

00:07:43.430 --> 00:07:44.450
are widows.

00:07:44.450 --> 00:07:48.600
Widows like, Susan, who is
one our clients in Uganda.

00:07:48.600 --> 00:07:50.220
And one of the things
we don't realize

00:07:50.220 --> 00:07:52.670
is that widows in
the developing world

00:07:52.670 --> 00:07:56.710
support about a half
a billion orphans.

00:07:56.710 --> 00:07:59.379
And so if you throw that family
off their little plot of land

00:07:59.379 --> 00:08:00.920
where they have
their little shelter,

00:08:00.920 --> 00:08:02.420
and their little
garden, and they're

00:08:02.420 --> 00:08:04.550
trying to sort of make
their way out of poverty,

00:08:04.550 --> 00:08:08.780
you have just decimated
their capacity to go forward.

00:08:08.780 --> 00:08:10.580
All of this I
emphasize is what we're

00:08:10.580 --> 00:08:13.031
calling everyday violence.

00:08:13.031 --> 00:08:15.280
Because many times when we
see or hear about violence,

00:08:15.280 --> 00:08:18.040
it's the stuff that
makes the headlines,

00:08:18.040 --> 00:08:20.230
the big wars, the genocide.

00:08:20.230 --> 00:08:23.490
I know something about
the phenomena of genocide.

00:08:23.490 --> 00:08:29.100
I was the Director of the UN's
genocide in Rwanda in 1994.

00:08:29.100 --> 00:08:33.000
And my job was to sort through
about 100 different mass graves

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:35.390
and massacre sites to see
what it looks like when

00:08:35.390 --> 00:08:39.190
human beings just unleash
violence against one another.

00:08:39.190 --> 00:08:40.820
And the things that
you notice when

00:08:40.820 --> 00:08:42.570
you're digging
through all of that,

00:08:42.570 --> 00:08:44.028
and you trying to
picture what's it

00:08:44.028 --> 00:08:46.690
like in the moment of
genocide to be in that place,

00:08:46.690 --> 00:08:49.367
you realize that that person
in the moment of terror

00:08:49.367 --> 00:08:51.450
is really not crying out
for someone to bring them

00:08:51.450 --> 00:08:55.260
food, or a doctor, or a
teacher, or a microloan, right?

00:08:55.260 --> 00:08:57.010
They're crying out for
someone to restrain

00:08:57.010 --> 00:08:58.760
the hand of the
machete that's coming

00:08:58.760 --> 00:09:00.740
towards them and their family.

00:09:00.740 --> 00:09:03.680
And this is what
we are identifying

00:09:03.680 --> 00:09:05.960
in terms of our
engagement with the poor.

00:09:05.960 --> 00:09:08.410
We know a great deal about
providing food, and medicine,

00:09:08.410 --> 00:09:10.610
and education, and
other basic needs,

00:09:10.610 --> 00:09:13.374
but what about the violence?

00:09:13.374 --> 00:09:15.540
And so this is an effort
through "The Locust Effect"

00:09:15.540 --> 00:09:18.699
to begin to open our
eyes to this epidemic.

00:09:18.699 --> 00:09:20.240
We're calling it
"The Locust Effect."

00:09:20.240 --> 00:09:22.410
It comes from these
stories from history

00:09:22.410 --> 00:09:23.880
that are very
powerful when you've

00:09:23.880 --> 00:09:26.510
got these poor farmers who
were sort of starting to scrape

00:09:26.510 --> 00:09:30.240
their way out of poverty, and
all of their work and ambition

00:09:30.240 --> 00:09:32.070
is in their crops, right?

00:09:32.070 --> 00:09:35.040
And they see them growing
and they offer great promise.

00:09:35.040 --> 00:09:37.710
And then one day, the
locust just descend.

00:09:37.710 --> 00:09:39.310
And honestly, in
a matter of hours,

00:09:39.310 --> 00:09:42.650
they will just wipe
out years of work.

00:09:42.650 --> 00:09:45.550
And this is the way violence
operates in the developing

00:09:45.550 --> 00:09:49.570
world for the poor who are
trying to get out of poverty.

00:09:49.570 --> 00:09:53.430
The violent predators just
come through and take it away.

00:09:53.430 --> 00:09:57.130
And so this means there are
tremendous implications for all

00:09:57.130 --> 00:09:58.980
of us who care about
global poverty.

00:09:58.980 --> 00:10:01.017
Probably all of us in
our lifetime in some way

00:10:01.017 --> 00:10:02.850
have been engaged with
that struggle, right?

00:10:02.850 --> 00:10:04.520
We've given some money.

00:10:04.520 --> 00:10:06.150
We've sought fresh water.

00:10:06.150 --> 00:10:07.520
We've sponsored a child.

00:10:07.520 --> 00:10:09.310
We've helped with
a school somewhere.

00:10:09.310 --> 00:10:11.750
We sponsored a microloan.

00:10:11.750 --> 00:10:15.080
And so all of these are
extremely important efforts,

00:10:15.080 --> 00:10:18.320
and we've seen a lot
of significant progress

00:10:18.320 --> 00:10:21.004
over the last 30 years
in addressing poverty.

00:10:21.004 --> 00:10:22.420
But what we're
starting to see now

00:10:22.420 --> 00:10:24.210
is we may be reaching
the limit of what

00:10:24.210 --> 00:10:27.040
can be done if we
don't begin to address

00:10:27.040 --> 00:10:30.420
the locust of violence who
can come in and just sweep

00:10:30.420 --> 00:10:32.580
the benefits of all
that effort away.

00:10:32.580 --> 00:10:34.980
The thing you'll notice
about the locust as well,

00:10:34.980 --> 00:10:37.490
is that not only do the
locust descend and destroy

00:10:37.490 --> 00:10:40.830
the fruit of the
farmer, but the farmer

00:10:40.830 --> 00:10:43.290
is not going to stop the locust.

00:10:43.290 --> 00:10:43.790
Right?

00:10:43.790 --> 00:10:47.830
We have to actually start
to do something differently.

00:10:47.830 --> 00:10:50.080
And so that's what "The
Locust Effect" is trying to do

00:10:50.080 --> 00:10:52.430
is to begin to change the
conversation about poverty

00:10:52.430 --> 00:10:54.340
to make sure that
we're mainstreaming

00:10:54.340 --> 00:10:56.400
the problem of violence.

00:10:56.400 --> 00:10:59.349
Because if that's
off the radar screen,

00:10:59.349 --> 00:11:01.140
we're going to miss
out on something that's

00:11:01.140 --> 00:11:03.089
undermining all
of our good work.

00:11:03.089 --> 00:11:04.880
One of the things that
the book tries to do

00:11:04.880 --> 00:11:08.050
is to try to say, well, why
is law enforcement so broken

00:11:08.050 --> 00:11:09.360
in the developing world?

00:11:09.360 --> 00:11:11.970
Why is there such
a lawless chaos

00:11:11.970 --> 00:11:14.250
for the average poor person?

00:11:14.250 --> 00:11:16.647
The book brings forth
really three surprises,

00:11:16.647 --> 00:11:18.480
and then one thing
that's not so surprising.

00:11:18.480 --> 00:11:20.530
The first surprise
is to realize, oh,

00:11:20.530 --> 00:11:22.780
all of these law enforcement
systems in the developing

00:11:22.780 --> 00:11:26.564
world, they were never
designed to stop crime.

00:11:26.564 --> 00:11:28.980
They were never designed to
protect the common poor person

00:11:28.980 --> 00:11:29.850
from violence.

00:11:29.850 --> 00:11:33.690
They were set up by colonial
powers over the first stage

00:11:33.690 --> 00:11:36.310
of the 20th century in order
to protect the government

00:11:36.310 --> 00:11:38.170
from the common people.

00:11:38.170 --> 00:11:41.290
And they've never been
re-engineered to actually

00:11:41.290 --> 00:11:42.310
enforce the law.

00:11:42.310 --> 00:11:44.810
And as a result, poor people
in the developing world

00:11:44.810 --> 00:11:46.060
now have great laws.

00:11:46.060 --> 00:11:48.430
This tremendous human rights
revolution over the last 50

00:11:48.430 --> 00:11:52.060
years has embedded great
laws in these countries.

00:11:52.060 --> 00:11:53.990
But what they don't
have is law enforcement.

00:11:53.990 --> 00:11:56.075
And it turns out that
that really matters.

00:11:56.075 --> 00:11:57.700
And mostly because
they've been saddled

00:11:57.700 --> 00:11:59.616
with these colonial
systems of law enforcement

00:11:59.616 --> 00:12:01.470
that have never
been re-engineered.

00:12:01.470 --> 00:12:03.050
The second reason
you find out is

00:12:03.050 --> 00:12:06.380
that there's been a massive
privatization of security

00:12:06.380 --> 00:12:07.880
in the developing world.

00:12:07.880 --> 00:12:10.642
So if you've been traveling in
the developing world at all,

00:12:10.642 --> 00:12:13.100
you'll sort of maybe notice,
especially in your first visit

00:12:13.100 --> 00:12:14.300
there, like almost
everywhere I go

00:12:14.300 --> 00:12:15.675
somebody's got a
gun guarding us.

00:12:15.675 --> 00:12:19.370
I mean, he's at the
restaurant, at the hotel,

00:12:19.370 --> 00:12:22.340
they're at the whatever sort
of commercial enterprise.

00:12:22.340 --> 00:12:26.409
There are just people
providing physical protection

00:12:26.409 --> 00:12:26.950
all the time.

00:12:26.950 --> 00:12:29.230
I was at the World
Economic Forum at Davos

00:12:29.230 --> 00:12:32.990
a few years ago with a
number of corporate leaders

00:12:32.990 --> 00:12:35.460
who have massive investments
in the developing

00:12:35.460 --> 00:12:39.176
world, huge
facilities, thousands

00:12:39.176 --> 00:12:40.300
and thousands of employees.

00:12:40.300 --> 00:12:42.750
And I just asked with all this
violence in the developing

00:12:42.750 --> 00:12:45.650
world that we're aware of,
like how do you guys protect

00:12:45.650 --> 00:12:47.034
your people and your property?

00:12:47.034 --> 00:12:48.700
And they all kind of
look at each other,

00:12:48.700 --> 00:12:51.500
and they actually almost
answer in unison to say,

00:12:51.500 --> 00:12:53.360
we pay for it.

00:12:53.360 --> 00:12:55.290
But if you think
about this, it's

00:12:55.290 --> 00:12:58.140
one thing if those with
wealth and influence

00:12:58.140 --> 00:13:02.040
leave the public school and the
public school kind of gets bad.

00:13:02.040 --> 00:13:05.105
Or you leave the public
transportation system,

00:13:05.105 --> 00:13:06.674
and the buses
become not so great.

00:13:06.674 --> 00:13:08.840
But what happens when the
people of wealth and power

00:13:08.840 --> 00:13:11.700
abandon the public
justice system?

00:13:11.700 --> 00:13:13.600
When the basic law
enforcement system

00:13:13.600 --> 00:13:16.420
is allowed to get worse,
and worse, and worse?

00:13:16.420 --> 00:13:18.300
That is the reality in
the developing world.

00:13:18.300 --> 00:13:19.820
And part of the
reason it stayed off

00:13:19.820 --> 00:13:23.120
the radar screen of
everybody is that the sector

00:13:23.120 --> 00:13:27.560
of wealthy folks in the
developing world from whom

00:13:27.560 --> 00:13:30.490
the economic growth
is coming from,

00:13:30.490 --> 00:13:32.000
have been able to
secure themselves

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:33.610
with private security.

00:13:33.610 --> 00:13:36.110
And so now, in the aggregate,
if you look at that country,

00:13:36.110 --> 00:13:38.150
it produces a decent
rate of economic growth.

00:13:38.150 --> 00:13:42.060
But for people who are living
off, let's say, $2 a day,

00:13:42.060 --> 00:13:45.210
that's about more
than 2 billion people,

00:13:45.210 --> 00:13:48.000
those folks can afford to
be safe and so they're not.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:53.620
The third other
surprising reason

00:13:53.620 --> 00:13:55.620
behind sort of the
brokenness of law enforcement

00:13:55.620 --> 00:13:58.510
is it's just not been the
subject of our investment.

00:13:58.510 --> 00:14:01.080
We've poured trillions of
dollars over the last 50 years

00:14:01.080 --> 00:14:04.690
into food systems, water
systems, public health systems,

00:14:04.690 --> 00:14:07.390
all totally vital, and
actually we haven't necessarily

00:14:07.390 --> 00:14:09.660
spent enough on trying
to engage those systems,

00:14:09.660 --> 00:14:12.690
because the poor need
all of those things.

00:14:12.690 --> 00:14:17.650
But we can't find even 1% of
all that expenditure and effort

00:14:17.650 --> 00:14:21.040
over the last 50 years that has
gone to building public justice

00:14:21.040 --> 00:14:23.640
systems that will actually
protect the poor from violence.

00:14:23.640 --> 00:14:26.190
So the third surprise is to
say, oh, we haven't actually

00:14:26.190 --> 00:14:29.420
really tried all that hard
to address this problem yet.

00:14:29.420 --> 00:14:32.680
The fourth explanation is
less surprising, perhaps,

00:14:32.680 --> 00:14:34.810
and that's just
the idea that there

00:14:34.810 --> 00:14:37.690
are people in power in
the developing world who

00:14:37.690 --> 00:14:40.320
have figured out how to
succeed in the absence

00:14:40.320 --> 00:14:41.860
of public justice, right?

00:14:41.860 --> 00:14:44.470
And so they now actually
would feel quite threatened

00:14:44.470 --> 00:14:48.180
if justice systems actually
started working in the way

00:14:48.180 --> 00:14:49.670
that they should.

00:14:49.670 --> 00:14:51.529
So that's the
diagnosis that we're

00:14:51.529 --> 00:14:53.320
trying to make here in
"The Locust Effect,"

00:14:53.320 --> 00:14:55.890
but then we try to make
a turn towards hope.

00:14:55.890 --> 00:14:57.840
And that is to
ask, OK great, this

00:14:57.840 --> 00:15:01.970
is totally depressing,
massive violence, grotesque.

00:15:01.970 --> 00:15:04.220
There's no way I'm
going to read this book.

00:15:04.220 --> 00:15:05.820
I'm depressed already.

00:15:05.820 --> 00:15:07.320
My wife is like,
yeah, give me a gin

00:15:07.320 --> 00:15:08.694
and tonic the next
time I'm going

00:15:08.694 --> 00:15:11.150
to try to read one
of your books, Gary.

00:15:11.150 --> 00:15:13.250
So yeah, the bad news is true.

00:15:13.250 --> 00:15:15.860
But this is part of where the
good news comes from, right?

00:15:15.860 --> 00:15:17.710
Because if you
think about the era

00:15:17.710 --> 00:15:19.570
when the AIDS
epidemic was really

00:15:19.570 --> 00:15:21.290
beginning to catch
momentum in the world,

00:15:21.290 --> 00:15:24.620
it required everybody to
open their eyes to something

00:15:24.620 --> 00:15:26.910
that was still a little
beneath the surface,

00:15:26.910 --> 00:15:29.360
but if unaddressed was
going to roll over just

00:15:29.360 --> 00:15:30.430
about everything else.

00:15:30.430 --> 00:15:32.090
And that's where we
are when it comes

00:15:32.090 --> 00:15:34.950
to the phenomenon of violence
in the developing world.

00:15:34.950 --> 00:15:39.380
So yes, we've got to wake up
to what is the tough reality.

00:15:39.380 --> 00:15:41.650
But the hope can be found
in a number of areas.

00:15:41.650 --> 00:15:44.060
The first is just in history.

00:15:44.060 --> 00:15:48.120
The truth is all of us enjoy
reasonably functioning justice

00:15:48.120 --> 00:15:52.080
systems here in New York, or you
can be in the San Francisco Bay

00:15:52.080 --> 00:15:55.190
Area, or Chicago, or you're
around the world in Paris

00:15:55.190 --> 00:15:57.920
or Tokyo, or various places
around the world that

00:15:57.920 --> 00:16:00.710
have the more developed
and affluent economies.

00:16:00.710 --> 00:16:03.250
And in each one of
those cities, you

00:16:03.250 --> 00:16:07.570
will find a history where 100
years ago, 150 years ago, you

00:16:07.570 --> 00:16:09.580
would have had the exact
same levels of just

00:16:09.580 --> 00:16:12.960
horrific violence and
horrific police corruption

00:16:12.960 --> 00:16:14.200
and brutality.

00:16:14.200 --> 00:16:16.220
In the book, we give
actually a series

00:16:16.220 --> 00:16:19.620
of descriptions to ask you,
like, guess which city this is?

00:16:19.620 --> 00:16:22.160
And you think your reading
from some just nightmare

00:16:22.160 --> 00:16:23.970
of a city in the
developing world,

00:16:23.970 --> 00:16:26.830
but actually it's one of
the cities that we live in.

00:16:26.830 --> 00:16:29.500
And you can see,
oh, every country

00:16:29.500 --> 00:16:32.560
begins with a difficult
situation of lawless violence,

00:16:32.560 --> 00:16:36.950
and you need to build systems
to protect the common citizenry.

00:16:36.950 --> 00:16:39.380
So what is the
process by which you

00:16:39.380 --> 00:16:42.910
move to law enforcement
that actually

00:16:42.910 --> 00:16:44.460
protects the common person?

00:16:44.460 --> 00:16:47.525
And you learn that this is
actually quite a doable thing.

00:16:47.525 --> 00:16:49.150
So you learn these
lessons from history

00:16:49.150 --> 00:16:52.280
and some clues about what might
happen in the developing world,

00:16:52.280 --> 00:16:54.370
but also some very
specific projects

00:16:54.370 --> 00:16:58.280
that we have highlighted in
the book where the success is

00:16:58.280 --> 00:17:01.670
really very encouraging
that if you focus on helping

00:17:01.670 --> 00:17:04.970
law enforcement do its job,
it has a dramatic result.

00:17:04.970 --> 00:17:09.359
One of those projects we did
in the second largest city

00:17:09.359 --> 00:17:12.650
of the Philippines
called Cebu which

00:17:12.650 --> 00:17:16.760
had a horrible problem
of child sex trafficking.

00:17:16.760 --> 00:17:20.770
The abduction and taking
of these young minor girls

00:17:20.770 --> 00:17:22.740
into the commercial
sex industry,

00:17:22.740 --> 00:17:25.609
and it's just a business
of rape for profit.

00:17:25.609 --> 00:17:29.830
And this was just taking
place at a horrific level

00:17:29.830 --> 00:17:31.470
in the city of Cebu.

00:17:31.470 --> 00:17:33.980
And we got some funding
from the Gates Foundation

00:17:33.980 --> 00:17:35.020
to try and experiment.

00:17:35.020 --> 00:17:37.400
Let's see whether or not it's
possible to do two things.

00:17:37.400 --> 00:17:39.480
Number one, let's see if
we can actually stand up

00:17:39.480 --> 00:17:42.490
local law enforcement,
which when we first

00:17:42.490 --> 00:17:45.500
began the project in the
city, it was actually

00:17:45.500 --> 00:17:47.870
on almost on the side of
sex trafficking, right?

00:17:47.870 --> 00:17:50.170
They're actually protecting
this and receiving funding

00:17:50.170 --> 00:17:52.380
for doing so.

00:17:52.380 --> 00:17:54.940
And by the way, the people
who carried out this project

00:17:54.940 --> 00:17:57.620
were our local
Filipino staff, right?

00:17:57.620 --> 00:18:00.364
Local Filipino lawyers,
Filipino criminal investigators,

00:18:00.364 --> 00:18:02.780
and social workers, and they
were trying to do two things.

00:18:02.780 --> 00:18:04.870
One, can we stand up that
local law enforcement

00:18:04.870 --> 00:18:07.475
through training and
programs of empowerment

00:18:07.475 --> 00:18:08.850
that allow them
to actually begin

00:18:08.850 --> 00:18:11.310
to send sex traffickers to jail?

00:18:11.310 --> 00:18:13.090
And if we do that,
will it actually

00:18:13.090 --> 00:18:15.600
then lower the amount
of sex trafficking

00:18:15.600 --> 00:18:16.877
of kids in the city?

00:18:16.877 --> 00:18:19.210
So we had some outside auditors
come in at the beginning

00:18:19.210 --> 00:18:21.410
and measure, well, how
much victimization of kids

00:18:21.410 --> 00:18:24.930
is there in the sex trade
before the project even begins.

00:18:24.930 --> 00:18:26.680
And then let's measure
it four years later

00:18:26.680 --> 00:18:28.660
to see what the impact is.

00:18:28.660 --> 00:18:31.830
So four years training
law enforcement,

00:18:31.830 --> 00:18:35.550
setting up specialized
units, fast tracking courts,

00:18:35.550 --> 00:18:37.740
providing good social
services to the victim,

00:18:37.740 --> 00:18:40.950
so they could actually make
their way through the justice

00:18:40.950 --> 00:18:42.580
system and receive healing.

00:18:42.580 --> 00:18:45.120
So after rescuing
hundreds of those victims

00:18:45.120 --> 00:18:48.450
and then sending about hundred
of the traffickers to jail,

00:18:48.450 --> 00:18:52.200
what was the outcome
after four years?

00:18:52.200 --> 00:18:53.820
The goal of the
project was to try

00:18:53.820 --> 00:18:57.910
to achieve a 20% reduction
in the victimization of kids

00:18:57.910 --> 00:18:59.280
in the commercial sex trade.

00:18:59.280 --> 00:19:02.030
But after four years, the
auditors came back and measured

00:19:02.030 --> 00:19:06.680
and they found a 79% reduction
in the victimization of kids

00:19:06.680 --> 00:19:08.380
in the commercial sex trade.

00:19:08.380 --> 00:19:12.820
And what you find is that
those who brutalize the poor,

00:19:12.820 --> 00:19:16.210
and children especially,
are not brave people.

00:19:16.210 --> 00:19:18.290
They're doing it
because they can.

00:19:18.290 --> 00:19:20.360
And once they start
getting in trouble for it,

00:19:20.360 --> 00:19:23.130
they start to leave the
children and the kids alone.

00:19:23.130 --> 00:19:25.580
So this is sort of the reality
that we're helping people

00:19:25.580 --> 00:19:27.410
to recover through the book.

00:19:27.410 --> 00:19:30.000
That, yes, there's a real
serious problem in the world,

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:34.430
but there's really
hopeful possibilities

00:19:34.430 --> 00:19:36.560
for making a difference.

00:19:36.560 --> 00:19:41.030
I would, of course, say that
the real purpose of this book

00:19:41.030 --> 00:19:43.910
is to begin to change the
conversation about poverty,

00:19:43.910 --> 00:19:44.650
right?

00:19:44.650 --> 00:19:46.114
Because if you
enter a discussion

00:19:46.114 --> 00:19:47.530
about global
poverty, if you think

00:19:47.530 --> 00:19:49.550
of the phenomenon
of yourself, you

00:19:49.550 --> 00:19:51.037
think of, OK, food and hunger.

00:19:51.037 --> 00:19:52.120
You think of medical care.

00:19:52.120 --> 00:19:53.040
You think of shacks.

00:19:53.040 --> 00:19:55.110
You think of bad
sanitation, bad education,

00:19:55.110 --> 00:19:57.110
the need for microloans,
all that sort of thing.

00:19:57.110 --> 00:19:59.530
But what does not
generally come to our mind

00:19:59.530 --> 00:20:02.970
is the violence that the poor
are chronically vulnerable to.

00:20:02.970 --> 00:20:04.920
And we just want to
change that conversation

00:20:04.920 --> 00:20:06.940
to make sure we're
asking the question, what

00:20:06.940 --> 00:20:08.640
about the violence?

00:20:08.640 --> 00:20:11.660
So we would like you to be
a part of that for sure.

00:20:11.660 --> 00:20:14.770
We'd love for you to buy
the book, first of all.

00:20:14.770 --> 00:20:17.240
Educate yourself, share
it with other people.

00:20:17.240 --> 00:20:19.710
If you buy the book
this week, we actually

00:20:19.710 --> 00:20:22.230
have some donors that
are going to match

00:20:22.230 --> 00:20:25.010
that with a $20 contribution
