00:30:10.010 --> 00:30:14.500
and they differ radically.

00:30:14.500 --> 00:30:17.036
So I'd like you to talk
a little bit about that.

00:30:17.036 --> 00:30:17.867
Perfect.

00:30:17.867 --> 00:30:18.950
GARY A. HAUGEN: Thank you.

00:30:18.950 --> 00:30:24.310
Yeah, certainly this has, over
just maybe the last 15 years,

00:30:24.310 --> 00:30:28.140
been looked at now as an
epidemiological matter

00:30:28.140 --> 00:30:29.420
from the public health sector.

00:30:29.420 --> 00:30:32.210
In fact, the World Health
Organization, it was about 10,

00:30:32.210 --> 00:30:35.190
15 years ago now, did
this massive global study

00:30:35.190 --> 00:30:37.500
about violence as
a health problem.

00:30:37.500 --> 00:30:41.530
And that's where much
of the data for the book

00:30:41.530 --> 00:30:43.840
is now coming from is the
World Health Organization

00:30:43.840 --> 00:30:45.850
and public health
experts are dialed

00:30:45.850 --> 00:30:51.270
into sort of the implications,
the ripple effects, of violence

00:30:51.270 --> 00:30:52.770
in the lives of poor people.

00:30:52.770 --> 00:30:55.300
What public health
has no experience in,

00:30:55.300 --> 00:30:58.400
however, is how you
stop the violence.

00:30:58.400 --> 00:31:00.770
And what is then
unfortunate is that world

00:31:00.770 --> 00:31:06.350
of law enforcement that actually
reduces violent behavior is

00:31:06.350 --> 00:31:09.189
sort of then off in its
own silo and public health

00:31:09.189 --> 00:31:10.230
has been off in its silo.

00:31:10.230 --> 00:31:11.670
And what we're
encouraging now is

00:31:11.670 --> 00:31:13.940
that those things come together.

00:31:13.940 --> 00:31:20.780
There's been some work done
on the economics of violence

00:31:20.780 --> 00:31:24.530
and the way that
undermines economic growth.

00:31:24.530 --> 00:31:27.310
But most of that's been
done in developed countries.

00:31:27.310 --> 00:31:30.560
So obviously, the data's
easier and more available,

00:31:30.560 --> 00:31:32.810
and it's a little
too bad the way

00:31:32.810 --> 00:31:35.050
our study tends to
run to the places

00:31:35.050 --> 00:31:37.740
where the examination of
the problem is easiest.

00:31:37.740 --> 00:31:39.490
That makes sense in a
certain kind of way,

00:31:39.490 --> 00:31:41.419
but we do need to bring
a lot of those lenses

00:31:41.419 --> 00:31:43.460
now into the developing
world to fully appreciate

00:31:43.460 --> 00:31:44.990
what's happening.

00:31:44.990 --> 00:31:49.634
The other question
is absolutely the one

00:31:49.634 --> 00:31:51.300
to be answered, which
is, wow, this just

00:31:51.300 --> 00:31:55.390
sounds like this massive generic
problem that actually is very

00:31:55.390 --> 00:32:00.490
localized in its manifestations,
and probably in its solutions,

00:32:00.490 --> 00:32:03.380
how do we begin to address it?

00:32:03.380 --> 00:32:05.450
One of our suggestions
in the book

00:32:05.450 --> 00:32:08.310
is precisely that what is
needed are some small scale

00:32:08.310 --> 00:32:12.240
experiments in some focused
places in the world.

00:32:12.240 --> 00:32:15.110
It's true, for instance, that
penicillin works everywhere

00:32:15.110 --> 00:32:15.740
in the world.

00:32:15.740 --> 00:32:16.800
And there are
certain ways in which

00:32:16.800 --> 00:32:18.174
law enforcement
works everywhere.

00:32:18.174 --> 00:32:20.940
As to say, in almost
every context,

00:32:20.940 --> 00:32:24.990
if human beings face a
cost for doing a behavior,

00:32:24.990 --> 00:32:28.020
they are reduced in their
likelihood of doing it.

00:32:28.020 --> 00:32:32.850
That's just true the same way
that penicillin just works.

00:32:32.850 --> 00:32:36.210
But what it takes in a
given society and culture

00:32:36.210 --> 00:32:38.240
for law enforcement
to be effective

00:32:38.240 --> 00:32:41.480
and to be supported
by the community,

00:32:41.480 --> 00:32:43.200
that's a different
equation everywhere.

00:32:43.200 --> 00:32:44.950
So we're interested
in supporting,

00:32:44.950 --> 00:32:47.220
and actually are
pursuing now, we

00:32:47.220 --> 00:32:50.190
have seven different
projects around the world,

00:32:50.190 --> 00:32:52.109
like the Cebu one,
which says, OK,

00:32:52.109 --> 00:32:53.900
not everywhere and in
regard to everything,

00:32:53.900 --> 00:32:55.970
but let's start in
a few laboratories

00:32:55.970 --> 00:32:57.360
and begin to experiment.

00:32:57.360 --> 00:33:00.820
What does it take in order
to do one thing first,

00:33:00.820 --> 00:33:03.040
stand up local law enforcement?

00:33:03.040 --> 00:33:06.810
Have the police, and the courts,
and the public justice system

00:33:06.810 --> 00:33:08.680
actually switch sides.

00:33:08.680 --> 00:33:10.495
So that instead of
preying upon the poor,

00:33:10.495 --> 00:33:12.440
they're actually
protecting the poor.

00:33:12.440 --> 00:33:14.524
And we've actually learned
quite a bit about that.

00:33:14.524 --> 00:33:16.190
And there's some
things you see that are

00:33:16.190 --> 00:33:17.490
common in most communities.

00:33:17.490 --> 00:33:19.750
And there's other things
that are very particular.

00:33:19.750 --> 00:33:21.420
And so what there
needs to be is just

00:33:21.420 --> 00:33:23.920
a much more robust
experimentation

00:33:23.920 --> 00:33:25.380
of this in the world.

00:33:25.380 --> 00:33:28.450
Because again, it's not going
to come from a silver bullet

00:33:28.450 --> 00:33:29.890
one size fits all.

00:33:29.890 --> 00:33:32.810
We did here in America, so
it's going to work over here.

00:33:32.810 --> 00:33:36.130
It's going to be a customized,
tailor-made, and community

00:33:36.130 --> 00:33:41.270
owned struggle in order to
bring justice for the poor.

00:33:41.270 --> 00:33:45.380
But that's when we need to start
to bring resources and effort

00:33:45.380 --> 00:33:48.960
to that's commensurate to
the size of the problem.

00:33:48.960 --> 00:33:50.360
Thank you.

00:33:50.360 --> 00:33:52.865
Other questions?

00:33:52.865 --> 00:33:53.490
Please, Justin.

00:33:56.982 --> 00:33:58.690
AUDIENCE: So being
that we are at Google,

00:33:58.690 --> 00:34:01.090
I'm curious as to what your
thoughts are on the role

00:34:01.090 --> 00:34:03.050
that technology
can play in being

00:34:03.050 --> 00:34:05.130
a constructive element
of these changes.

00:34:05.130 --> 00:34:06.860
GARY A. HAUGEN: Yeah,
well, one of things

00:34:06.860 --> 00:34:08.750
I'm hoping technology
will do is just sort

00:34:08.750 --> 00:34:12.300
of shrink the world in
terms of awareness, right?

00:34:12.300 --> 00:34:15.000
Because one of the things that's
difficult in this era is we

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:17.550
can live on different
planetary systems, right?

00:34:17.550 --> 00:34:21.620
I mean, the idea that there are
millions of people in slavery.

00:34:21.620 --> 00:34:25.610
The idea that sexual assault
can take place at such a level

00:34:25.610 --> 00:34:28.469
that you're more likely
to fall in the shower

00:34:28.469 --> 00:34:30.690
than to ever go to jail for it.

00:34:30.690 --> 00:34:33.040
Those can feel so far from us.

00:34:33.040 --> 00:34:36.579
And one of the things
that this era has done

00:34:36.579 --> 00:34:38.120
is shrink that world
so that everyone

00:34:38.120 --> 00:34:39.780
can be much more aware of this.

00:34:39.780 --> 00:34:43.179
One of things that we're
also starting to bring

00:34:43.179 --> 00:34:44.800
is visualization of this.

00:34:44.800 --> 00:34:47.719
I mean, our teams now do
undercover investigations

00:34:47.719 --> 00:34:50.590
that expose these kinds of
abuses that are taking place.

00:34:50.590 --> 00:34:53.052
And that stuff can now
almost be shared real time

00:34:53.052 --> 00:34:53.760
around the world.

00:34:53.760 --> 00:34:55.239
It's going to be
harder and harder

00:34:55.239 --> 00:34:58.520
to get away with this stuff.

00:34:58.520 --> 00:35:00.360
But once we have
exposure, then we

00:35:00.360 --> 00:35:04.430
need to move actually
towards solutions.

00:35:04.430 --> 00:35:07.150
The other thing that technology
has a capacity to do,

00:35:07.150 --> 00:35:09.020
amazingly, is bring
accountability

00:35:09.020 --> 00:35:10.915
and transparency.

00:35:10.915 --> 00:35:13.040
You're starting to see this
in the corruption realm

00:35:13.040 --> 00:35:18.180
now where instead
of paying a police

00:35:18.180 --> 00:35:21.620
officer for your ticket on
the spot, you go to some kiosk

00:35:21.620 --> 00:35:23.370
somewhere electronically
and pay for that.

00:35:23.370 --> 00:35:25.661
So it isn't even the opportunity
for the police officer

00:35:25.661 --> 00:35:26.900
to take the money.

00:35:26.900 --> 00:35:31.277
Or to like be able to
go to register and say,

00:35:31.277 --> 00:35:33.610
yeah, there were supposed to
be police in our community,

00:35:33.610 --> 00:35:36.200
and if this is day 20 where
we've never seen anybody,

00:35:36.200 --> 00:35:41.010
and all that sort of data and
that picture starts to appear.

00:35:41.010 --> 00:35:47.390
So we're even exploring the ways
in which satellite imagery is

00:35:47.390 --> 00:35:51.360
able to actually see
where the brick kilns are

00:35:51.360 --> 00:35:55.530
in South Asia where there's
more likely to be slavery.

00:35:55.530 --> 00:35:59.440
And the tracking of
criminality, the new VP

00:35:59.440 --> 00:36:04.170
of investigations at IJM is
the former director of NCIS.

00:36:04.170 --> 00:36:07.390
And he's very interested in
trying to leverage technology

00:36:07.390 --> 00:36:09.910
in this crime fighting
effort around the world.

00:36:09.910 --> 00:36:12.660
So I'm not the one,
certainly, to be

00:36:12.660 --> 00:36:14.660
able to suggest what all
the possibilities are,

00:36:14.660 --> 00:36:17.250
but what I would love to
do is to see those who have

00:36:17.250 --> 00:36:19.670
this expertise and these
capacities just sort of join

00:36:19.670 --> 00:36:20.795
the struggle and the fight.

00:36:23.392 --> 00:36:25.210
Yes sir.

00:36:25.210 --> 00:36:28.260
AUDIENCE: Just as an idea,
with the proliferation

00:36:28.260 --> 00:36:30.831
of cell phones
throughout the world.

00:36:30.831 --> 00:36:32.080
What about the self-reporting?

00:36:32.080 --> 00:36:33.270
GARY A. HAUGEN: Absolutely.

00:36:33.270 --> 00:36:35.200
Yeah, you do notice
that right now.

00:36:35.200 --> 00:36:37.420
There are very few
bad things that

00:36:37.420 --> 00:36:42.304
