Because that's what's
it's going to take.

00:39:02.130 --> 00:39:04.240
It's going to be
sort of taking what

00:39:04.240 --> 00:39:07.490
we think we know about improving
these law enforcement systems,

00:39:07.490 --> 00:39:10.220
and then testing it, and
measuring, and seeing what

00:39:10.220 --> 00:39:13.010
actually does work and let's
put more resources on the things

00:39:13.010 --> 00:39:14.300
actually work.

00:39:14.300 --> 00:39:15.520
Yeah.

00:39:15.520 --> 00:39:17.460
AUDIENCE: So you
talked about violence

00:39:17.460 --> 00:39:18.995
as contributing
cause to poverty.

00:39:18.995 --> 00:39:19.870
GARY A. HAUGEN: Yeah.

00:39:19.870 --> 00:39:23.490
AUDIENCE: What about the
causes of the violence itself?

00:39:23.490 --> 00:39:27.027
How much of that is,
perhaps, need driven?

00:39:27.027 --> 00:39:27.860
GARY A. HAUGEN: Yes.

00:39:27.860 --> 00:39:28.901
AUDIENCE: Is it cultural?

00:39:28.901 --> 00:39:30.190
Is it innate?

00:39:30.190 --> 00:39:32.200
Does mankind just suck?

00:39:32.200 --> 00:39:35.940
A very small
percentage of people

00:39:35.940 --> 00:39:39.090
having a very large
impact on the community,

00:39:39.090 --> 00:39:42.700
or can you discuss
violence as an effect?

00:39:42.700 --> 00:39:45.186
GARY A. HAUGEN: I'd love to.

00:39:45.186 --> 00:39:46.560
I will tell you,
any of you who'd

00:39:46.560 --> 00:39:49.340
taken a genocide course
in college or something

00:39:49.340 --> 00:39:52.220
and look at genocide, I
mean, it's disturbing.

00:39:52.220 --> 00:39:55.340
The capacity for the
very common person

00:39:55.340 --> 00:39:57.790
to become very, very violent
in regard to their neighbors

00:39:57.790 --> 00:39:58.830
is amazing.

00:39:58.830 --> 00:40:02.230
And as the investigator
of the Rwanda genocide,

00:40:02.230 --> 00:40:06.950
the story is there that once
the restraints were taken off,

00:40:06.950 --> 00:40:09.350
and you could do
anything to your neighbor

00:40:09.350 --> 00:40:16.430
to take their land, to
sexually assault the neighbor's

00:40:16.430 --> 00:40:19.820
daughter, and to
kill your neighbor,

00:40:19.820 --> 00:40:24.990
this is unleashed with
quite frightening ferocity.

00:40:24.990 --> 00:40:28.560
So there is something
in human beings

00:40:28.560 --> 00:40:31.560
that just needs to
be accounted for.

00:40:31.560 --> 00:40:36.210
And we've seen in history, too,
that the way that most violence

00:40:36.210 --> 00:40:38.520
is restrained is
by law enforcement.

00:40:38.520 --> 00:40:40.540
That's why we all
have law enforcement.

00:40:40.540 --> 00:40:43.150
None of you are choosing to
live in a neighborhood that

00:40:43.150 --> 00:40:45.000
has no law enforcement.

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:47.900
But it would be interesting,
and if I had a whiteboard here,

00:40:47.900 --> 00:40:50.830
you could draw a graph of crime.

00:40:50.830 --> 00:40:54.230
And on the left axis, you
would put different kinds

00:40:54.230 --> 00:40:58.000
of crime and their frequency.

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:01.040
And then what you
do is draw a line

00:41:01.040 --> 00:41:04.934
on the horizontal axis of risk.

00:41:04.934 --> 00:41:06.350
And what you would
measure is sort

00:41:06.350 --> 00:41:10.770
of the elasticity of different
kinds of crime to risk.

00:41:10.770 --> 00:41:15.060
And at the top is what we
call crime of opportunity.

00:41:15.060 --> 00:41:17.550
You do it because you
can get away with it,

00:41:17.550 --> 00:41:19.220
and there's no risk at all.

00:41:19.220 --> 00:41:21.530
And so you do it
because you can.

00:41:21.530 --> 00:41:24.970
Then there's crime
of desperation.

00:41:24.970 --> 00:41:27.990
Maybe I'm poor, and I feel
like I got a break that window

00:41:27.990 --> 00:41:31.040
and steal that bread, because
I'm really quite desperate.

00:41:31.040 --> 00:41:32.850
Then there's crime of necessity.

00:41:32.850 --> 00:41:37.700
You feel like in order to hold
power, or in order to survive,

00:41:37.700 --> 00:41:38.850
you must commit this crime.

00:41:38.850 --> 00:41:42.370
And sometimes when the state
commits crime, like torture,

00:41:42.370 --> 00:41:44.900
they feel like they
have to do this, right?

00:41:44.900 --> 00:41:45.772
It's necessity.

00:41:45.772 --> 00:41:47.730
And then if you go way
down towards the bottom,

00:41:47.730 --> 00:41:49.560
you have social
pathology and deviancy.

00:41:49.560 --> 00:41:51.489
A person actually can't
even stop themselves

00:41:51.489 --> 00:41:53.280
from committing that
crime, because there's

00:41:53.280 --> 00:41:54.930
a sickness involved.

00:41:54.930 --> 00:41:59.400
All of those have different
elasticity to risk.

00:41:59.400 --> 00:42:05.060
So the pathology, man, somebody
who's really a social deviant,

00:42:05.060 --> 00:42:08.800
and you see this with
pedophilia and other-- there you

00:42:08.800 --> 00:42:11.240
can actually ratchet
up to risk level.

00:42:11.240 --> 00:42:13.550
And it drops maybe a little
bit, but that line actually

00:42:13.550 --> 00:42:15.934
stays pretty steady,
because in that they end up

00:42:15.934 --> 00:42:18.100
going to jail in many
respects if there's decent law

00:42:18.100 --> 00:42:19.100
enforcement.

00:42:19.100 --> 00:42:21.035
Then you have
crime of necessity,

00:42:21.035 --> 00:42:23.670
and likewise, it
takes a little dip,

00:42:23.670 --> 00:42:28.270
but then it stays
pretty steady, too.

00:42:28.270 --> 00:42:30.860
Desperation, yeah, it
takes a fall a little bit,

00:42:30.860 --> 00:42:34.070
but when desperation
feels like necessity,

00:42:34.070 --> 00:42:35.810
it also flattens out.

00:42:35.810 --> 00:42:38.150
But crime of
opportunity, amazing.

00:42:38.150 --> 00:42:39.990
That stuff goes out
a little bit by risk,

00:42:39.990 --> 00:42:43.716
and then it drops off to
zero, because it was crime

00:42:43.716 --> 00:42:45.090
because I could
get away with it.

00:42:45.090 --> 00:42:47.680
Now I can't get away with it,
I'm just not doing any more.

00:42:47.680 --> 00:42:51.600
The vast, vast, vast majority
of violence against the poor

00:42:51.600 --> 00:42:53.940
is crime of opportunity.

00:42:53.940 --> 00:42:58.187
And so we can with law
enforcement reduce that amount,

00:42:58.187 --> 00:43:00.270
and then we'll be wrestling
with the kind of crime

00:43:00.270 --> 00:43:04.310
that we're dealing with in our
more developed countries, which

00:43:04.310 --> 00:43:07.390
is the hard problems of
social deviancy and people

00:43:07.390 --> 00:43:09.970
who are desperate and have
no hope, all kinds of things

00:43:09.970 --> 00:43:14.450
involved here, substance abuse
and a whole set of factors

00:43:14.450 --> 00:43:16.620
But all this crime
of opportunity, this

00:43:16.620 --> 00:43:18.860
is where all the crime is
happening against the poor

00:43:18.860 --> 00:43:19.750
because they can.

00:43:19.750 --> 00:43:24.120
And that is a very,
very doable proposition.

00:43:24.120 --> 00:43:26.240
Long lecture on the
elasticity of crime

00:43:26.240 --> 00:43:29.480
than you weren't
expecting today.

00:43:29.480 --> 00:43:30.650
I apologize in advance.

00:43:33.240 --> 00:43:34.640
Any other questions?

00:43:34.640 --> 00:43:35.235
Yes.

00:43:35.235 --> 00:43:37.375
AUDIENCE: What about the
real structural situation

00:43:37.375 --> 00:43:40.060
of just the police and underpay?

00:43:40.060 --> 00:43:43.290
And the fact that in many
countries being a cop

00:43:43.290 --> 00:43:44.416
is a license to steal.

00:43:44.416 --> 00:43:45.540
GARY A. HAUGEN: Absolutely.

00:43:45.540 --> 00:43:46.190
Yeah.

00:43:46.190 --> 00:43:48.100
So that has to be addressed.

00:43:48.100 --> 00:43:49.170
That's the bad news.

00:43:49.170 --> 00:43:51.410
The good news is it's
totally addressable.

00:43:51.410 --> 00:43:54.970
In other words, it's not
rocket science in a way.

00:43:54.970 --> 00:43:56.655
I worked the first
half of my career,

00:43:56.655 --> 00:43:59.030
and Victor currently is that
the US Department of Justice

00:43:59.030 --> 00:44:00.050
dealing with police corruption.

00:44:00.050 --> 00:44:01.160
So in every society,
you are going

00:44:01.160 --> 00:44:02.950
to have police corruption,
but it actually

00:44:02.950 --> 00:44:05.760
turns out there's things
that you can do about this.

00:44:05.760 --> 00:44:08.120
And one of the case studies
that we look at in the book

00:44:08.120 --> 00:44:11.740
is the study of the
country of Georgia,

00:44:11.740 --> 00:44:14.120
which is a former
Soviet Republic.

00:44:14.120 --> 00:44:16.830
And it was one of the most
corrupt countries in the world.

00:44:16.830 --> 00:44:19.680
In fact, in 2003,
Transparency International

00:44:19.680 --> 00:44:22.350
ranked it as like 143
out of a 190 countries

00:44:22.350 --> 00:44:23.675
in being the most corrupt.

00:44:23.675 --> 00:44:25.360
I mean, more corrupt
than any country

00:44:25.360 --> 00:44:26.610
that we currently work in.

00:44:26.610 --> 00:44:29.130
And we work in some
very corrupt countries.

00:44:29.130 --> 00:44:32.860
And yet there was a
political election,

00:44:32.860 --> 00:44:36.480
a party was committed
to a platform, really

00:44:36.480 --> 00:44:38.250
of anti-corruption
came into power.

00:44:38.250 --> 00:44:42.310
And they seriously went after
police corruption first.

00:44:42.310 --> 00:44:44.700
Just to give you an idea,
police corruption in Georgia,

00:44:44.700 --> 00:44:48.380
you would pay $10,000 to
the police commissioner

00:44:48.380 --> 00:44:50.900
in order to get hired as a
police officer for which you

00:44:50.900 --> 00:44:53.230
are paid $10.

00:44:53.230 --> 00:44:55.444
Why would you pay
$10,000 for a job that

00:44:55.444 --> 00:44:56.985
was only going to
pay to $10 a month?

00:44:56.985 --> 00:44:59.180
It's because you were
given a license really

00:44:59.180 --> 00:45:02.650
to use that authority
then to steal from people.

00:45:02.650 --> 00:45:04.650
And what happened as a
result, is the state just

00:45:04.650 --> 00:45:06.941
started producing more and
more police officers, right?

00:45:06.941 --> 00:45:08.000
Because I get this now.

00:45:08.000 --> 00:45:09.660
The more police officers
there are, the more money

00:45:09.660 --> 00:45:11.350
I make as the
commissioner of police.

00:45:15.300 --> 00:45:19.820
As far as payment, let
me just address that.

00:45:19.820 --> 00:45:22.040
So what they did is they
came in very committed

00:45:22.040 --> 00:45:23.120
to addressing this.

00:45:23.120 --> 00:45:26.450
The thing they did is they
fired 16,000 police officers

00:45:26.450 --> 00:45:27.790
in a single day in the capital.

00:45:27.790 --> 00:45:29.450
Sent them all
home, and the place

00:45:29.450 --> 00:45:31.260
was safer and better for it.

00:45:31.260 --> 00:45:33.020
Right?

00:45:33.020 --> 00:45:35.170
Just sent them all
home and rebuilt

00:45:35.170 --> 00:45:37.559
the police from the ground up.

00:45:37.559 --> 00:45:39.100
One of the things
that they had to do

00:45:39.100 --> 00:45:42.852
was then pay the
police very well,

00:45:42.852 --> 00:45:44.560
because they want to
recruit good people,

00:45:44.560 --> 00:45:48.330
and equip them well,
and supply them well.

00:45:48.330 --> 00:45:53.010
And as a result a lot of this
committed effort, by 2010

00:45:53.010 --> 00:45:56.120
seven years later, the
Georgian police force

00:45:56.120 --> 00:45:59.100
was rated as less corrupt
than the US police,

00:45:59.100 --> 00:46:01.890
the German police,
or the French police.

00:46:01.890 --> 00:46:03.895
The World Bank wrote
up the study of this,

00:46:03.895 --> 00:46:06.390
and it's featured in the book.

00:46:06.390 --> 00:46:08.610
Because I actually
fortuitously sat next

00:46:08.610 --> 00:46:10.182
to the prime
minister of Georgia,

00:46:10.182 --> 00:46:11.640
because I was amazed
at this story.

00:46:11.640 --> 00:46:13.430
And I got a chance to talk
to him over dinner about it.

00:46:13.430 --> 00:46:15.513
And he said people say
that corruption is culture.

00:46:15.513 --> 00:46:18.260
He says, corruption is a choice.

00:46:18.260 --> 00:46:20.010
And when a society
makes the choice

00:46:20.010 --> 00:46:22.290
to begin to root this
out, it's possible.

00:46:22.290 --> 00:46:25.320
And the place to start
amazingly is the police,

00:46:25.320 --> 00:46:27.160
because it sounds
counterintuitive in a way,

00:46:27.160 --> 00:46:29.076
because that's like the
worst, scariest place.

00:46:29.076 --> 00:46:32.220
But if you think about
it, corruption is a crime.

00:46:32.220 --> 00:46:34.830
It's stealing from other people.

00:46:34.830 --> 00:46:38.760
And if you have crime of
corruption in the crime

00:46:38.760 --> 00:46:42.280
fighting force, your capacity
to root it out from other places

00:46:42.280 --> 00:46:43.880
is just about zero.

00:46:43.880 --> 00:46:46.586
So we've kind of laughed
about it and joked about it.

00:46:46.586 --> 00:46:48.710
Oh, the police are corrupt
in the developing world.

00:46:48.710 --> 00:46:50.380
No, no, that's a
serious problem,

00:46:50.380 --> 00:46:52.230
because that has
undermined your capacity

00:46:52.230 --> 00:46:54.063
to deal with any
corruption in your country.

00:46:54.063 --> 00:46:55.840
And so that's the bad news.

00:46:55.840 --> 00:46:58.810
The good news is, because
this is a command structure,

00:46:58.810 --> 00:47:00.670
leadership can
actually change that

00:47:00.670 --> 00:47:03.165
quite quickly if there's
commitment from the top.

00:47:05.990 --> 00:47:06.830
Any other questions?

00:47:06.830 --> 00:47:09.179
Yes.

00:47:09.179 --> 00:47:10.970
AUDIENCE: You make a
sensible point, right?

00:47:10.970 --> 00:47:12.760
We buy the story and everything.

00:47:12.760 --> 00:47:16.090
Why [INAUDIBLE], they have
the money and everything,

00:47:16.090 --> 00:47:17.549
why nothing has happened?

00:47:17.549 --> 00:47:19.090
GARY A. HAUGEN:
Yeah, Great question,

00:47:19.090 --> 00:47:20.590
which is why isn't
everybody already

00:47:20.590 --> 00:47:21.950
addressing this already?

00:47:21.950 --> 00:47:23.910
That's a hard question, too.

00:47:23.910 --> 00:47:27.670
And actually, I've spent the
last 10 years going around

00:47:27.670 --> 00:47:29.250
to almost every
smart person I can.

00:47:29.250 --> 00:47:31.631
Because as they started
to come to our eyes

00:47:31.631 --> 00:47:34.130
from just the daily work in the
developing world, it's like,

00:47:34.130 --> 00:47:35.566
hey, isn't this
is a big problem,

00:47:35.566 --> 00:47:37.190
and isn't this just
going to get worse,

00:47:37.190 --> 00:47:39.170
and don't we need to
get out in front of it?

00:47:39.170 --> 00:47:41.650
There are some reasons why
it's been very difficult.

00:47:41.650 --> 00:47:44.480
One of the reasons
is that the people

00:47:44.480 --> 00:47:47.200
who are immersed in
the academic and sort

00:47:47.200 --> 00:47:50.580
of technical disciplines
of fighting poverty

00:47:50.580 --> 00:47:53.220
are just very foreign to the
world of law enforcement,

00:47:53.220 --> 00:47:53.720
right?

00:47:53.720 --> 00:47:56.970
So it's the economist, the
agronomist, the clean water

00:47:56.970 --> 00:48:00.460
engineers, the
public health folks.

00:48:00.460 --> 00:48:07.720
What it takes to actually
do a highly effective law

00:48:07.720 --> 00:48:09.920
enforcement is a completely
different discipline.

00:48:09.920 --> 00:48:11.710
So these worlds have
been very far apart,

00:48:11.710 --> 00:48:13.850
and we're trying to
bring them together.

00:48:13.850 --> 00:48:17.430
The second thing is that
it's been dangerous and scary

00:48:17.430 --> 00:48:22.669
for aid organizations to engage
supporting law enforcement

00:48:22.669 --> 00:48:24.960
in the developing world,
because law enforcement is not

00:48:24.960 --> 00:48:26.105
a benign system.

00:48:26.105 --> 00:48:28.200
Right?

00:48:28.200 --> 00:48:30.050
Because it's a coercive system.

00:48:30.050 --> 00:48:32.850
It's the coercive arm of the
state, and if it turns bad,

00:48:32.850 --> 00:48:34.060
it commits abuses.

00:48:34.060 --> 00:48:36.050
Now you helped empower
it, and you're like, oh,

00:48:36.050 --> 00:48:37.300
now we're in trouble for that.

00:48:37.300 --> 00:48:39.720
So we actually made
illegal after human rights

00:48:39.720 --> 00:48:43.900
abuses in the 70s and
80s for aid organizations

00:48:43.900 --> 00:48:45.810
to assist police.

00:48:45.810 --> 00:48:48.809
Now it seemed like a good
idea to like stop the abuses,

00:48:48.809 --> 00:48:50.350
but the answer to
bad law enforcement

00:48:50.350 --> 00:48:52.680
is not going to be
no law enforcement.

00:48:52.680 --> 00:48:54.720
So we need to say,
yeah, there's a bad way

00:48:54.720 --> 00:48:57.140
to assist law enforcement.

00:48:57.140 --> 00:48:59.600
But they're also clearly
now some good ways to do it,

00:48:59.600 --> 00:49:01.570
and that's what
we need to pursue.

00:49:01.570 --> 00:49:03.560
Thanks again for your
patience and interest.

00:49:03.560 --> 00:49:07.150
And please buy the book,
and share the video,

00:49:07.150 --> 00:49:09.380
and help us change the
discussion on the Millennium

00:49:09.380 --> 00:49:10.130
Development Goals.

00:49:10.130 --> 00:49:12.280
Thanks very much.

